1
00:00:01,398 --> 00:00:02,159
Hi, everyone.

2
00:00:03,720 --> 00:00:07,263
Thank you for coming to our public information session.

3
00:00:08,124 --> 00:00:09,765
This is the Charter Study Committee.

4
00:00:10,786 --> 00:00:12,788
I'm going to just, I'm Milva McDonald.

5
00:00:12,908 --> 00:00:21,195
I'm the chair of the committee, and I'm going to introduce the committee members that are here, and then I'm going to hand the mic over to Ron Giovino.

6
00:00:21,887 --> 00:00:24,270
who is one of our committee members.

7
00:00:24,310 --> 00:00:32,179
We also have Phyllis Morrison, Eunice Brown, Paulette Vander Kloot, Anthony Andriodala, and Jean Zotter.

8
00:00:34,942 --> 00:00:39,888
Ron's gonna talk a little bit about the committee, what we've been doing, and I'm gonna hand it over.

9
00:00:41,763 --> 00:00:42,143
Thank you.

10
00:00:43,223 --> 00:00:44,064
Good evening, everybody.

11
00:00:45,004 --> 00:01:03,788
For those of you who are watching us for the first time, just to briefly talk a little bit about, it was back in 2022 in November that the mayor appointed this committee to research the current charter, which hadn't been reviewed in almost four decades.

12
00:01:05,809 --> 00:01:08,749
It's an 11 member, are we still 11 members?

13
00:01:08,769 --> 00:01:10,250
11 member committee.

14
00:01:12,991 --> 00:01:17,412
We do meet every Thursday, every first Thursday of the month.

15
00:01:18,073 --> 00:01:20,174
That's been pretty consistent, both on Zoom.

16
00:01:21,694 --> 00:01:22,335
You can watch it.

17
00:01:24,215 --> 00:01:36,841
So the reason why this meeting is of particular importance is we're targeted to present our recommendations and our thoughts on the charter in the fall of 2024.

18
00:01:40,622 --> 00:01:47,631
Currently, we've done dozens of listening sessions, interviews, government official interviews.

19
00:01:50,221 --> 00:01:51,842
many different people's interviews.

20
00:01:52,322 --> 00:01:56,443
Our survey, which ends this month, is ready to be completed.

21
00:01:56,463 --> 00:02:00,624
Do we have like 700 responses to the survey?

22
00:02:00,644 --> 00:02:08,946
600 responses, so we're gonna be compiling that information as another resource for us as we make our decisions.

23
00:02:09,867 --> 00:02:13,968
This is our third public event at City Hall.

24
00:02:14,688 --> 00:02:33,073
And we've also done various, we've appeared at various city events during the summer, Wright's Pond and different events, just to get the word out that the charter is a very important part of how the city runs and it's time for change and now is the time.

25
00:02:33,833 --> 00:02:39,055
We've also partnered with the Collins Center for Public Management from UMass Boston.

26
00:02:40,315 --> 00:02:48,419
They guide us when we need guidance, and they'll be with us through the process as we make our presentation in the fall.

27
00:02:49,900 --> 00:02:56,803
The commitment from my fellow committee members has always been that we're dedicated to listening,

28
00:02:57,757 --> 00:03:04,762
And we're dedicated to do that with great curiosity about what you think and also a great open mind.

29
00:03:04,962 --> 00:03:15,509
And I can tell you, you know, we all come with our prejudices and we all come in with our thoughts, but the conversations that we've been having have really made a difference in what we do.

30
00:03:15,549 --> 00:03:21,553
And it's extremely important for us as a goal is to listen to the fellow citizens and also

31
00:03:22,634 --> 00:03:28,055
tell you what our thoughts are so we can, as a unit, make this charter very successful.

32
00:03:31,036 --> 00:03:43,138
So if you haven't seen any of our meetings, our monthly meetings, you will know, our subcommittee meetings, you would know that the level of research that these folks have done on this committee is mind-boggling.

33
00:03:43,858 --> 00:03:48,339
The detail has been incredible, and it's really allowed us to make our recommendations.

34
00:03:49,625 --> 00:03:53,046
Now our presentation will be filled with recommendations.

35
00:03:53,606 --> 00:04:02,529
If you know, we've looked at the role of the mayor in the city, we've looked at ward representation for both the city council and currently looking at the school committee.

36
00:04:03,670 --> 00:04:09,492
But the process for us is once we make our presentation to the city council and the mayor,

37
00:04:10,392 --> 00:04:19,298
They can accept what we say, they can amend anything they want, they can remove or add anything they want prior to it going to the state house for review.

38
00:04:20,679 --> 00:04:26,843
Once the state has reviewed it and approved it, it comes back to you, the voters, and that's really the key part.

39
00:04:28,203 --> 00:04:33,004
There's no more powerful person than each one who has one vote on this charter.

40
00:04:33,985 --> 00:04:36,325
The person who has more power is the one who actually votes.

41
00:04:37,005 --> 00:04:41,106
So that's where we're at.

42
00:04:41,406 --> 00:04:55,850
It's been a great year plus learning and listening, and I think charter has become more of a regularly used word in the city at different events, different discussions, on government TV.

43
00:04:56,730 --> 00:05:11,514
So I think we're moving in the right direction and we've got a lot more work to do as today, the end of January, it's really the time for us to start picking the final, make the final decisions and start moving forward.

44
00:05:11,894 --> 00:05:22,797
And there's a lot of things left on the table and our hope is that the citizens will guide us and tell us what's the most important pieces that we need to do to put in our presentation in the fall.

45
00:05:25,197 --> 00:05:38,163
All the input has been tremendous, it's really been helpful, and I speak for myself, it's been eye-opening, but it's a long process and we're getting close to the end, so that's why these meetings become more and more important.

46
00:05:38,383 --> 00:05:40,683
So that's what I have to say.

47
00:05:40,703 --> 00:05:42,984
Thanks, Ron.

48
00:05:46,521 --> 00:05:53,244
Yeah, and to echo what Ron said, we are sort of at a turning point in our process.

49
00:05:53,444 --> 00:06:02,148
We're going to start, we have provisionally voted on several important issues, but we're really going to be

50
00:06:03,879 --> 00:06:12,047
buckling down and doing a lot of votes, making our final decisions on recommendations and drafting a new charter.

51
00:06:12,548 --> 00:06:15,210
And that's going to be happening in the coming months.

52
00:06:15,230 --> 00:06:18,333
So we'd love to see you at our meetings.

53
00:06:19,815 --> 00:06:25,621
And right now we want to just open it up to see if anybody has any questions.

54
00:06:30,332 --> 00:06:32,374
or comments.

55
00:06:32,534 --> 00:06:36,538
If you're on Zoom, you can raise your hand, or if you're in the hall, just come up to the mic.

56
00:06:49,811 --> 00:06:51,453
So we don't have any questions.

57
00:06:53,711 --> 00:07:02,336
Okay, so this is going to probably be pretty short since our main objective here was to try to listen to folks.

58
00:07:02,516 --> 00:07:08,059
But before we wrap up, I will just say some of the

59
00:07:09,060 --> 00:07:29,097
provisional decisions we've made so far, and this has been based on our own conversations, our research, our looking at historical data on representation in the city, our survey results, public feedback, and larger pieces of

60
00:07:30,518 --> 00:07:33,340
that we're going to be doing a lot of research.

61
00:07:33,360 --> 00:07:34,081
Uh there we are.

62
00:07:34,121 --> 00:07:38,825
We've decided not to keep a mayor form of government, a mayor council form of government.

63
00:07:40,006 --> 00:07:45,210
And the committee has provisionally voted to recommend hybrid ward representation.

64
00:07:46,371 --> 00:07:46,991
With eight.

65
00:07:47,291 --> 00:07:48,873
So Medford has eight wards.

66
00:07:49,033 --> 00:07:49,153
That

67
00:07:55,718 --> 00:08:07,443
The school committee is something that we're still diving into research on, so decisions have not been made on that yet, but we have.

68
00:08:07,643 --> 00:08:16,707
And we're also looking at the balance of power because that has been some of the main concerns that we've heard from people are

69
00:08:20,024 --> 00:08:24,828
and the balance of power between the mayor and the City Council.

70
00:08:24,848 --> 00:08:25,988
So we're looking at that.

71
00:08:27,710 --> 00:08:41,039
We have voted to give the City Council, to incorporate in our draft charter, the power for the City Council to confirm mayoral appointments to multi-member boards.

72
00:08:42,921 --> 00:08:46,383
At our next meeting, we're gonna be looking at term lengths.

73
00:08:47,824 --> 00:09:00,675
which is a trickier question than you would think because there's a lot of moving parts with that in terms of when elections are held, etc.

74
00:09:02,116 --> 00:09:04,397
We're also going to be looking at the question of term limits.

75
00:09:04,417 --> 00:09:09,361
Then we will be looking at the issue of

76
00:09:13,378 --> 00:09:21,503
Our current charter does not have anything in it about how compensation for election officials is decided.

77
00:09:22,484 --> 00:09:23,765
So we will be looking at

78
00:09:26,048 --> 00:09:32,194
putting a process for that into the charter or recommending a process for that, putting it into our draft charter.

79
00:09:33,735 --> 00:09:38,519
And we also are going to be looking at the budget timeline.

80
00:09:39,480 --> 00:09:50,590
So these are some of, and very exciting also, we will be looking at, our current charter has no section on citizen participation mechanisms.

81
00:09:50,790 --> 00:09:51,491
So right now,

82
00:09:53,612 --> 00:10:05,983
whatever a group of citizens can do in terms of trying to initiate change within Medford through ballot questions or whatever has to come from state law.

83
00:10:07,044 --> 00:10:16,552
So we can look at that and try to put something in the charter that would allow for citizens to

84
00:10:18,644 --> 00:10:24,130
do more of that sort of participatory change in the city.

85
00:10:24,690 --> 00:10:29,235
So those are sort of the main highlights of what we have left.

86
00:10:29,315 --> 00:10:30,316
There's also a lot of

87
00:10:32,434 --> 00:10:39,578
you know, administrative practices and kind of standard pieces that have to be done as well.

88
00:10:39,658 --> 00:10:50,645
So we have a lot of work ahead of us, but we've done a lot already and we hope you'll get in touch with us and tell us what you think.

89
00:10:51,965 --> 00:10:54,447
And thanks everybody for tuning in.

90
00:10:57,915 --> 00:11:02,316
Yes, our survey is closing on January 31st.

91
00:11:02,976 --> 00:11:12,559
So if you go to www.medfordma.org slash charter study, it will take you to the survey.

92
00:11:13,119 --> 00:11:14,919
Please take the survey if you haven't already.

93
00:11:16,019 --> 00:11:17,500
Also there you will find

94
00:11:18,947 --> 00:11:27,311
all our materials, the recordings of every meeting we've had, minutes, materials that were presented at the meeting.

95
00:11:28,512 --> 00:11:44,319
For instance, all the historical data on representation of city councilors in the city that we collected as part of our process to decide on whether to recommend ward representation, all that can be found

96
00:11:45,461 --> 00:11:46,122
on that page.

97
00:11:46,783 --> 00:11:51,432
So we hope you'll take a look and thank you all for tuning in.

98
00:11:54,494 --> 00:11:58,217
just before we, as I said, this is a listening session.

99
00:11:59,518 --> 00:12:04,883
So, you know, your comments in terms of what do you think about the process?

100
00:12:05,484 --> 00:12:06,364
What can we do better?

101
00:12:07,245 --> 00:12:08,266
What can we do less of?

102
00:12:09,047 --> 00:12:09,847
What have we missed?

103
00:12:10,668 --> 00:12:12,129
What are the things that are important to you?

104
00:12:12,149 --> 00:12:15,172
I'll probably give you a few more minutes to step in.

105
00:12:15,232 --> 00:12:16,213
I know there's some folks on

106
00:12:17,054 --> 00:12:17,955
Zoom listening in.

107
00:12:17,975 --> 00:12:27,925
We have a guest here in the hall, but if anybody wants to make a comment before Milva adjourns this meeting, I would suggest that now is a good time to do that.

108
00:12:28,165 --> 00:12:28,446
Thanks.

109
00:12:32,410 --> 00:12:37,836
If you are on Zoom, you can raise your hand or come up to the mic.

110
00:12:53,256 --> 00:12:53,456
Okay.

111
00:13:02,402 --> 00:13:08,806
If there are no questions or comments, we will adjourn.

112
00:13:11,588 --> 00:13:11,928
Thank you.

